<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>The Olmstead v. United States decision established that:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Wiretapping required warrants</option>
            <option letter="b">Wiretapping without warrants was constitutional</option>
            <option letter="c">Privacy rights were absolute</option>
            <option letter="d">Electronic surveillance was illegal</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The 1928 Olmstead v. United States decision established that wiretapping without a warrant did not violate the Fourth Amendment's protection against unreasonable searches because there was no physical intrusion into private property. This ruling gave law enforcement significant latitude in conducting electronic surveillance, particularly during Prohibition enforcement, and remained the legal standard until being overturned in 1967.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
